"clicking-stream-frog":{n:"Clicking Stream Frog",c:"Amphibian",s:"Frog",sz:"Small",cl:"Brown",i:"ğŸ¸",wp:"Strongylopus_grayii",d:"A small frog named for its distinctive clicking call heard near streams and dams. Brown with a dark mask through the eye. One of the first frogs to call after winter rains. Common but easily overlooked.",w:"2-5 g",l:"3-4.5 cm",life:"3-5 years",act:"Nocturnal",diet:"Insectivore â€” small insects",cs:"Least Concern"},
"common-river-frog":{n:"Common River Frog",c:"Amphibian",s:"Frog",sz:"Small",cl:"Green & Brown",i:"ğŸ¸",wp:"Amietia_delalandii",d:"Found along permanent water sources. They produce a loud chorus at night, especially after rain. Green and brown mottled skin provides excellent camouflage among riverside vegetation.",w:"10-30 g",l:"4-8 cm",life:"5-8 years",act:"Nocturnal",diet:"Insectivore â€” insects, spiders",cs:"Least Concern"},
"painted-reed-frog":{n:"Painted Reed Frog",c:"Amphibian",s:"Frog",sz:"Small",cl:"Multicolored",i:"ğŸ¸",wp:"Hyperolius_marmoratus",d:"One of the most variable frogs in southern Africa â€” individuals can be striped, spotted, or plain in white, brown, yellow, orange, and pink. At only 3 cm, incredibly tiny. Their whistling chorus is a sound of African evenings.",w:"1-3 g",l:"2-3 cm",life:"3-4 years",act:"Nocturnal",diet:"Insectivore â€” small flying insects",cs:"Least Concern"},
"raucous-toad":{n:"Raucous Toad",c:"Amphibian",s:"Toad",sz:"Small",cl:"Brown",i:"ğŸ¸",wp:"Sclerophrys_capensis",d:"A stocky toad with warty brown skin. Named for the raucous, duck-like quacking chorus produced by males after rain. Found throughout the park near any form of standing water. Can tolerate drier conditions than most frogs.",w:"20-60 g",l:"6-10 cm",life:"10+ years",act:"Nocturnal",diet:"Insectivore â€” beetles, ants, termites",cs:"Least Concern"},
