"white-rhinoceros":{n:"White Rhinoceros",c:"Mammal",s:"Big 5",sz:"Very Large",cl:"Grey",i:"ğŸ¦",wp:"White_rhinoceros",d:"The larger of Africa's two rhino species with a wide, flat mouth designed for grazing. 'White' comes from the Dutch 'wijd' meaning wide, referring to its lip shape. More sociable than black rhinos, sometimes forming groups called crashes.",w:"1,700-2,300 kg",l:"3.4-4 m",life:"40-50 years",act:"Day & night",diet:"Grazer â€” grasses",cs:"Near Threatened"},
"south-african-giraffe":{n:"South African Giraffe",c:"Mammal",s:"Herbivore",sz:"Very Large",cl:"Tawny & Brown",i:"ğŸ¦’",wp:"South_African_giraffe",d:"The tallest living terrestrial animal. Their distinctive patchy coat patterns are unique like fingerprints. A giraffe's heart weighs about 11 kg and generates twice the blood pressure of humans to push blood up their long necks. They sleep only 30 minutes per day.",w:"800-1,200 kg",l:"4.6-5.5 m tall",life:"20-25 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Browser â€” acacia, leaves",cs:"Vulnerable"},
"blue-wildebeest":{n:"Blue Wildebeest",c:"Mammal",s:"Herbivore",sz:"Large",cl:"Blue-Grey",i:"ğŸ¾",wp:"Blue_wildebeest",d:"Also known as the brindled gnu. Named for the blue-grey sheen of their coat. Calves can stand and run within minutes of birth. Often seen grazing in mixed herds with zebra, as the combination improves predator detection.",w:"180-270 kg",l:"1.7-2.4 m",life:"20 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Grazer â€” short grasses",cs:"Least Concern"},
"impala":{n:"Impala",c:"Mammal",s:"Antelope",sz:"Medium",cl:"Reddish Brown",i:"ğŸ¦Œ",wp:"Impala",d:"One of the most graceful African antelope, famous for their spectacular leaping ability â€” bounding up to 3 metres high and 10 metres in length. Only males carry lyre-shaped horns. Distinctive black markings on the rump resemble the letter M.",w:"40-76 kg",l:"1.2-1.6 m",life:"12-15 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Mixed feeder â€” grasses, leaves",cs:"Least Concern"},
"waterbuck":{n:"Waterbuck",c:"Mammal",s:"Antelope",sz:"Large",cl:"Grey-Brown",i:"ğŸ¦Œ",wp:"Waterbuck",d:"A large, robust antelope with a distinctive white ring on the rump. Always found near water as they are dependent on regular drinking. Their coarse, oily coat has a strong musky smell that deters predators. Only males carry long, curved horns.",w:"160-300 kg",l:"1.7-2.4 m",life:"18 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Grazer â€” grasses",cs:"Least Concern"},
"nyala":{n:"Nyala",c:"Mammal",s:"Antelope",sz:"Large",cl:"Brown",i:"ğŸ¦Œ",wp:"Nyala",d:"One of the most sexually dimorphic antelope â€” males are dark brown-grey with vertical white stripes and a shaggy mane, while females are bright chestnut with clear stripes. Males have impressive spiral horns. Shy browsers found in dense thickets.",w:"55-140 kg",l:"1.4-1.95 m",life:"16 years",act:"Diurnal/Crepuscular",diet:"Browser â€” leaves, fruit, grasses",cs:"Least Concern"},
"southern-ground-hornbill":{n:"Southern Ground Hornbill",c:"Bird",s:"Ground Bird",sz:"Very Large",cl:"Black & Red",i:"ğŸ¦",wp:"Southern_ground_hornbill",d:"The largest hornbill in the world. Lives in cooperative family groups where only the dominant pair breeds. Their deep booming calls carry up to 5 km. Critically endangered in South Africa with fewer than 1,500 remaining in the wild.",w:"2.2-6.2 kg",l:"90-129 cm",life:"50-70 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Carnivore â€” insects, snakes, frogs",cs:"Vulnerable"},
